{"timestamp": 1772714058.7034616, "task_id": "gen-20260305180810-8252", "task_type": "analysis", "description": "Compare quicksort vs heapsort", "result": {"success": true, "agent": "analyst", "duration": 8.937668561935425, "output": "Both are O(n log n) average case, but they differ in ways that matter in practice.\n\n**Quicksort**\n- Average: O(n log n), Worst: O(n²) — bad pivot selection (e.g., sorted input with naive pivot)\n- In-place, but not stable\n- Cache-friendly due to sequential memory access patterns\n- Smaller constant factors in practice — often faster in real benchmarks\n- Worst case avoidable with randomized or median-of-3 pivot\n\n**Heapsort**\n- Always O(n log n) — no bad cases\n- In-place, but not stable\n- Poor cache performance — heap operations jump around in memory\n- Larger constant factors, slower in practice despite same asymptotic complexity\n\n**When to pick which**\n\n- Default choice → quicksort (or introsort, which is quicksort + heapsort fallback)\n- Guaranteed worst-case matters → heapsort\n- Stability required → neither; use mergesort or timsort\n- Most standard library sorts (Python, Java, Rust) use timsort or introsort, not pure quicksort\n\nThe short version: quicksort wins on average hardware due to cache behavior, heapsort wins when you need predictable worst-case guarantees without extra memory.", "tokens": {"input": 2769, "output": 350}}, "retry_count": 0, "total_attempts": 1}
{"timestamp": 1772714068.7324283, "task_id": "gen-20260305180810-7864", "task_type": "analysis", "description": "Compare quicksort vs mergesort", "result": {"success": true, "agent": "analyst", "duration": 9.821269273757935, "output": "Here's a practical comparison:\n\n**Time Complexity**\n- Both average O(n log n)\n- Quicksort worst case: O(n²) — happens with bad pivot selection on sorted/nearly-sorted data\n- Mergesort worst case: O(n log n) — always consistent\n\n**Space Complexity**\n- Quicksort: O(log n) stack space (in-place)\n- Mergesort: O(n) — needs auxiliary array for merging\n\n**Key tradeoffs**\n\nQuicksort wins on:\n- Cache performance — works in-place, better memory locality\n- Real-world speed — lower constant factors despite same Big-O\n- No extra memory allocation\n\nMergesort wins on:\n- Stability — preserves order of equal elements\n- Predictable performance — no worst-case surprises\n- Linked lists — merging is O(1) extra space vs arrays\n- External sorting — when data doesn't fit in memory\n\n**When to use which**\n\nGo with quicksort when you need raw speed on in-memory arrays and stability doesn't matter. Most standard library sorts (C's `qsort`, early Java) used it for this reason.\n\nGo with mergesort (or a hybrid) when you need stable sorting, or you're sorting linked lists or external data. Java's `Arrays.sort` for objects uses Timsort, which is merge-based.\n\n**In practice**, most modern languages use hybrid approaches — Python's Timsort, Rust's pattern-defeating quicksort — because neither pure algorithm wins in all cases.", "tokens": {"input": 3052, "output": 403}}, "retry_count": 0, "total_attempts": 1}
