{"timestamp": 1772726807.2480986, "task_id": "gen-20260305180810-7431", "task_type": "analysis", "description": "Compare heapsort vs mergesort", "result": {"success": true, "agent": "analyst", "duration": 14.511521100997925, "output": "Here's a breakdown of the two:\n\n**Time Complexity**\n- Both are O(n log n) in all cases (best, average, worst)\n- Mergesort is consistently O(n log n); heapsort's constant factors are typically worse in practice\n\n**Space Complexity**\n- Heapsort: O(1) — in-place\n- Mergesort: O(n) — needs auxiliary space for merging\n\n**Stability**\n- Mergesort: stable (preserves order of equal elements)\n- Heapsort: not stable\n\n**Cache Performance**\n- Mergesort wins here — sequential memory access patterns are cache-friendly\n- Heapsort jumps around the heap array, causing more cache misses\n\n**Practical Performance**\n- Mergesort tends to be faster in practice despite same asymptotic complexity, largely due to cache behavior\n- Heapsort is preferred when memory is constrained\n\n**When to use which**\n- Need stable sort → mergesort\n- Memory-constrained environment → heapsort\n- Sorting linked lists → mergesort (natural fit, no random access needed)\n- External sorting (large datasets on disk) → mergesort (sequential I/O)\n\nIn most standard library implementations, neither is used alone — introsort (quicksort + heapsort fallback) or timsort (mergesort variant) are more common because they combine the best properties of multiple algorithms.", "tokens": {"input": 2799, "output": 375}}, "retry_count": 0, "total_attempts": 1}
